 and even nonsensical quality of what things say; their interests are so radically different from ours that we either destroy or worship them. Existing outside systems of exchange and the priorities of civil society, things in fact advertise the dissident obscurity common to slave narratives all the way from Aesop and Phaedrus to Frederick Douglass and Primo Levi, a way of meaning only what is said, never saying what is meant. This is what Defoe's Roxana calls "the Sense of Things," and it is found in sounds, substances, and images rather than conventional signs.This major work illuminates not only "it narratives," but also eighteenth-century literature, the rise of the novel, and the genealogy of the slave narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPersonal belongings in literature. 0aProperty in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAesop.  aArabian Nights.  aBacon, Francis.  aBlunden, Edmund.  aBrandeis, Louis.  aCopyright Act.  aDefoe, Daniel.  aDeutsch, Helen.  aDon Quixote (Cervantes).  aFantomina (Haywood).  aGallagher, Catherine.  aGildon, Charles.  aGothic novel.  aGrub Street.  aHawkesworth, John.  aHeidegger, Martin.  aHollar, Wenceslaus.  aHume, David.  aJünger, Ernst.  aKirkman, Francis.  aLennox, Charlotte.  aLeviathan (Hobbes).  aLocke, John.  aMichelangelo.  aNarcissus.  aNavy Board.  aOedipus.  aQuintilian.  aRambler.  aadvertisements.  aauthority.  acamera obscura.  achapbook.  acuriosities.  aekphrases.  aentail.  afiction.  afolk tales.  aidentity.  aidolatry.  aimagination.  ait-narratives.  ajustice.  alabor.  amagic.  ametempsychosis.  amuru.  aobjects.  apanpsychism.  apassion.  aprobability.  arealism.08iTitle 